{"timestamp": "2025-12-06 14:10:11.250504", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nScope and goal\n- Validate end-to-end connectivity for enterprise users to the local DNS and web services.\n- Detect anomalies, localize the faulty device(s), and identify root cause.\n\nSummary assessment\n- Layer-3 routing/OSPF between access subnets and the server farm is healthy: end-to-end reachability and latency are normal with 0% loss.\n- DNS service at 10.200.0.2 is up and responds correctly for the local zone.\n- Host in 10.1.1.0/24 operates normally (resolves and reaches web services by name).\n- Host in 10.2.1.0/24 experiences consistent failures when accessing services by FQDN (webX.local, web99.local) but succeeds when using IPs. This is due to receiving a public DNS server via DHCP instead of the internal DNS.\n- Secondary observation: TCP/53 from 10.2.1.0/24 to 10.200.0.2 appears blocked/timed out, though UDP DNS queries succeed.\n\nEvidence\n\n1) Reachability and routing\n- Ping matrix: All tested pairs show 0% loss and low RTTs, including:\n  - host_1_1_1_1 -> dns_server (10.200.0.2): ok, ~2.5 ms RTT.\n  - host_2_1_1_1 -> dns_server (10.200.0.2): ok, ~2.9 ms RTT.\n  - hosts -> web_server_2 (10.200.0.5): ok.\n- Conclusion: OSPF/L3 forwarding across access, distribution, core, and server farm is functioning as expected.\n\n2) Host IP configuration\n- host_1_1_1_1 (10.1.1.10/24, GW 10.1.1.1): resolv.conf nameserver 10.200.0.2.\n- host_2_1_1_1 (10.2.1.10/24, GW 10.2.1.1): resolv.conf nameserver 8.8.8.8 (public).\n- DHCP server config (/etc/dhcp/dhcpd.conf):\n  - subnet 10.1.1.0: option domain-name-servers 10.200.0.2.\n  - subnet 10.2.1.0: option domain-name-servers 8.8.8.8.\n- Observation: The two access subnets receive different DNS servers; 10.2.1.0/24 is pointed at a public resolver, which does not serve the local “.local” zone.\n\n3) DNS service and name resolution behavior\n- DNS server netstat shows bind on 10.200.0.2:53 and 127.0.0.1:53 (LISTEN), confirming service is up.\n- host_1_1_1_1:\n  - getent hosts web0.local -> 10.200.0.3 (OK).\n  - curl http://web0.local, http://web1.local, http://web2.local, http://web3.local: all succeed with total times ~1.0–1.17 s.\n  - curl http://web99.local: succeeds consistently (total ~1.01–1.26 s).\n  - curl http://10.200.0.5: succeeds (total ~2.5–3.4 s), confirming HTTP path is fine.\n- host_2_1_1_1:\n  - resolv.conf: nameserver 8.8.8.8 (public).\n  - getent hosts web99.local: timeouts.\n  - nslookup web99.local 10.200.0.2: succeeds (resolves to 10.200.0.7), proving internal DNS works if queried directly.\n  - curl http://web99.local and web0.local–web3.local: repeated 5.0 s timeouts (no name lookup progress), consistent with querying a public resolver that has no knowledge of the local zone.\n  - curl http://10.200.0.5 (by IP): succeeds with totals ~1.0–3.5 s, confirming transport path is fine and the issue is name resolution only.\n\n4) DNS transport (TCP vs UDP)\n- host_2_1_1_1 -> 10.200.0.2 TCP/53: test indicates timeout (“TCP53_BLOCKED”).\n- However, nslookup to 10.200.0.2 succeeds (implies UDP/53 OK).\n- Not directly impacting the observed failure because the host isn’t using 10.200.0.2 by default; but blocking TCP/53 would reduce DNS resiliency and certain behaviors requiring TCP fallback.\n\n5) Lease timing (observation)\n- DHCP default-lease-time 30; max-lease-time 60. Host leases show valid_lft ~40–50 seconds, unusually short for enterprise clients. Not the root cause here but noteworthy operationally.\n\nAnomalies detected\n- Host 10.2.1.10 cannot resolve internal FQDNs (webX.local, web99.local), leading to application timeouts, while direct IP access works. This is an internal DNS reachability/usage anomaly (by configuration).\n- TCP/53 from 10.2.1.0/24 to 10.200.0.2 appears blocked/timed out, although UDP DNS queries work.\n\nFault localization\n- Primary fault localized to the DHCP server configuration:\n  - dhcp_server -> dhcpd.conf supplies the wrong DNS server for subnet 10.2.1.0/24 (public 8.8.8.8 instead of internal 10.200.0.2).\n- Secondary (potential) fault lies in path filtering or host firewall affecting TCP/53 to dns_server from 10.2.1.0/24.\n\nRoot cause\n- Misconfiguration on the DHCP server: subnet 10.2.1.0/24 is assigned a public DNS server (8.8.8.8), which does not host the enterprise “.local” zone, causing name resolution failures for local services (including the load balancer web99.local and the local web servers) from that subnet.\n\nImpact\n- Users in 10.2.1.0/24 cannot access enterprise services by name; they experience ~5s timeouts on HTTP requests to web*.local and web99.local.\n- Services remain accessible by IP address, confirming no L3 routing or server-side application outage.\n- Users in 10.1.1.0/24 are unaffected.\n\nNo remediation steps are provided, per instructions.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 11780, "output_tokens": 4811, "total_tokens": 16591, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 11136}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 3392}}}
